4

The next chunk of code adds columns to the monona data set which contain the fitted values (\(\hat{y}_i\) in the notation of the lecture notes) and the residuals after fitting a straight line simple regression model to the data. You do not need to examine or understand this code chunk.

## Fit the model
fit = lm(duration ~ year1, data = monona)

## Add fitted values and residuals to the data set
monona = monona %>% 
  mutate(fitted = fitted(fit),
         residuals = residuals(fit))

Make a plot of the residuals versus year1. Add a horizontal line with an intercept at zero. (See example from lecture using geom_hline()). Add a smooth curve to this residual plot as well.

ggplot(monona, aes(x = year1, y = residuals)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

Using the informal interpretation discussed in lecture, what evidence from the residual plot indicates that a straight-line simple regression model for the duration that Lake Monona is frozen versus time is an adequate model?

Response

Because the average smooth curve equally below or above the straight-line

5

The next chunk of code adds a variable winter_day to the monona data set which counts the number of days after the previous June 30 on which Lake Monona first freezes. You do not need to examine or understand this code.

## add winter_day = #days of first freeze after June 30
monona = monona %>% 
  mutate(winter_day = as.numeric(
    first_freeze - ymd(str_c(year1,"-06-30"))))

Make a histogram of this variable with bins of width 5 centered and one bin centered at 154 (which corresponds to December 1). Select different colors to shade the interior and the boundaries of the bars. Add appropriate axis labels and a plot title.

## Make the histogram
ggplot(monona, aes(x = winter_day)) +
  geom_histogram(center = 154, binwidth = 5, fill = "forestgreen", color = "darkviolet") +
  xlab("Days after June 30") +
  ylab("Count") +
  ggtitle("Lake Monona First Freeze Distribution",
          subtitle = "1851 - 2021")

6

Recreate the plot from the previous problem, but modify scale of the x axis so that the axis is labeled with the dates Dec 1, Dec 16, Dec 31, Jan 15, Jan 30 at the values 154, 169, 184, 199, 214. You will use the function scale_x_continuous() to change the scale of the x axis. (Hint: See an example changing the scale of the y axis in lecture 5).

ggplot(monona, aes(x = winter_day)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, center = 154, color = "darkviolet", fill = "forestgreen") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(154,214,by=15),
                     labels = c("Dec 1", "Dec 16", "Dec 31", "Jan 15", "Jan 30")) +
  xlab("Days after June 30") +
  ylab("Count") +
  ggtitle("Lake Monona First Freeze Distribution",
          subtitle = "1851 - 2021")

7

The next chunk of code reads in the exoplanet data discussed in the course notes, reduces the data set to a few variables, renames these, and drops observations with missing masses. You do not need to read or comment on this code chunk.

## Note: the file begins with 100 comment lines which we skip
exo = read_csv("../../data/exoplanets_default_2021-06-15.csv", skip = 100) %>% 
  select(pl_name, hostname, discoverymethod, pl_bmasse) %>%
  rename(planet = pl_name,
         star = hostname,
         method = discoverymethod,
         mass = pl_bmasse) %>% 
  drop_na(mass)

The following code chunk makes a boxplot of the planet masses (units are in Earth masses, so 10 is ten times the mass of Earth) versus the method of discovery.

ggplot(exo, aes(x = method, y = mass)) +
  geom_boxplot()

What are some faults that this basic plot has?

Response

  1. the method’s name are stacked together
  2. y scale doesn’t fit

The next code chunk adds several lines of code. Explain the effect that each additional line highlighted with a comment does to the plot. Try running the code with the indicated lines commented out or seek information from R Studio help, the R for Data Science textbook, or a Google search about each command and argument to understand what it does.

## You may need to install the scales package if the next line causes an error
library(scales)

## Make the side-by-side boxplots
ggplot(exo, aes(x = method, y = mass)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ## (A) What does the following line do?
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10", label = comma) +
  xlab("Method of Detection") +
  ylab("Mass (Earth masses)") +
  ## (B) What does the following line do?
  coord_flip()

Response

(A) effect of scale_y_continuous()

trans = “log10”

transform y axes into log10 scale

label = comma

Adjust the number format and make it more readable by adding comma

(B) effect of coord_flip()

Flip the direction of the plot, put the method into y sacle

Create a density plot of the variable mass from the exoplanet data set. Use different colors for the interior of the density and the boundary line. Describe the shape of exoplanet masses.

ggplot(exo) + 
  geom_density(aes(x = mass), color = "darkviolet", fill = "forestgreen")

Response

L shape, density declines rapidly at first and finally flateens out

Make a second density plot for the base-10 logarithm of masses instead. Describe the shape of the log-transformed exoplanet masses.

ggplot(exo) + 
  geom_density(aes(x = mass), color = "darkviolet", fill = "forestgreen") +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10", label = comma)

Response

M shape, there are two peaks in this shape
